{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.03,0.05,0.09,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15372"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with her boyfriend due to an emotional outburst this morning, during which she threatened to slit her wrists following an argument about who would make breakfast. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her boyfriend reports frequent fights, multiple episodes of low mood lasting a few days, and numerous past relationships. He states, \u0022\u003Cem\u003EShe is so unpredictable. One day she says I am the best boyfriend in the whole world and the next day she says that I am the worst person ever.\u0022 \u003C/em\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Vitals are within normal limits. There are no visible injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following defence mechanisms is this patient most likely exhibiting in her relationship with her boyfriend?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acting out","Displacement","Projection","Reaction formation","Splitting"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with borderline personality disorder (BPD), a cluster B personality disorder more commonly seen in women. The key features exhibited here include unstable relationships, emotional instability, and recurrent suicidal threats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplitting\u003C/strong\u003E is the defence mechanism most likely being exhibited by this patient. Splitting is a cardinal feature of BPD where individuals view people or situations in extreme, black-and-white terms. This is evident in the boyfriend\u0027s statement that she sees him as \u0022the best boyfriend in the whole world\u0022 one day and \u0022the worst person ever\u0022 the next.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActing out\u003C/strong\u003E involves impulsive, often aggressive behaviours in response to emotional distress. While the patient\u0027s suicidal threat could be considered acting out, the question specifically asks about the defence mechanism in her relationship with her boyfriend, which is better explained by splitting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisplacement\u003C/strong\u003E is redirecting emotions from their original source to a less threatening target. There\u0027s no evidence of this in the given scenario, where the patient\u0027s emotions seem directly related to her interactions with her boyfriend.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjection\u003C/strong\u003E involves attributing one\u0027s own unacceptable thoughts or emotions to others. The scenario doesn\u0027t provide any examples of the patient projecting her feelings onto her boyfriend or others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReaction formation\u003C/strong\u003E is the expression of feelings or behaviours opposite to one\u0027s true feelings. This isn\u0027t demonstrated in the given scenario, where the patient\u0027s expressed emotions seem to align with her internal state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing patients with BPD, it\u0027s crucial to maintain consistent boundaries, provide a stable therapeutic environment, and be aware of the potential for rapid shifts in the patient\u0027s perception of others, including healthcare providers. Long-term management often involves dialectical behaviour therapy or other forms of psychotherapy, alongside careful consideration of any pharmacological interventions for specific symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Splitting is a cardinal feature of borderline personality disorder.","Patients with borderline personality disorder often exhibit unstable relationships, emotional instability, and recurrent suicidal threats or attempts."],"references":["Burland J. Splitting as A Consequence of Severe Abuse in Childhood. Psychiatric Clinics of North America. 1994;17(4):731-742. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7877900/","Kulacaoglu F, Kose S. Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD): In the Midst of Vulnerability, Chaos, and Awe. Brain Sci. 2018 Nov 18;8(11):201. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6266914/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38032"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38032"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T08:58:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T09:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/697"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Borderline personality disorder","synonyms":["BPD"],"description":n